@aureleoules Thanks for the detailed review. I addressed all the suggestions.

> the user asks for a new address, they should get a new address

@luke-jr as mentioned earlier, that's why a new RPC was created instead of using `getnewaddress`, just so the user doesn't think a new address will be generated.

How about returning a JSON object with some warnings for new labels to explicit that new labels are not new identities?

<details>
<summary>Example</summary>

```bash
./src/bitcoin-cli -testnet -rpcwallet=sp1 getsilentaddress client1 
{
  "address": "tsp071pp809z56vwvyqhwc4fsjq8vhjw6yyguzv2u9hnwt3jvyl2ha49nwqtsc8w9",
  "index": 7,
  "label": "client1",
  "warnings": "This address is not a new identity. It is a re-use of an existing identity with a different label."
}
./src/bitcoin-cli -testnet -rpcwallet=sp1 getsilentaddress client1
{
  "address": "tsp071pp809z56vwvyqhwc4fsjq8vhjw6yyguzv2u9hnwt3jvyl2ha49nwqtsc8w9",
  "label": "client1",
  "index": 7
}
./src/bitcoin-cli -testnet -rpcwallet=sp1 getsilentaddress client2
{
  "address": "tsp081pp809z56vwvyqhwc4fsjq8vhjw6yyguzv2u9hnwt3jvyl2ha49nwqyqkdah",
  "index": 8,
  "label": "client2",
  "warnings": "This address is not a new identity. It is a re-use of an existing identity with a different label."
}
./src/bitcoin-cli -testnet -rpcwallet=sp1 getsilentaddress client2
